2025, day 94

Good morning from Asia.

All the focus today is on the reaction to the Trump tariffs;

Markets plunged, stocks down, bond yields down, commodities down, oil down a lot, and the dollar down. The least hysterical take was “meltdown”;

Some point out the tariffs are a body blow to “factory Asia” and to globalisation as we’ve known it;

Others point out inflation will rise short term, although if oil keeps falling that will offset a lot; 

Many flag a near-term risk of recession. Yet a collapse in bond yields helps narrow the U.S. fiscal deficit and refinance debts just as a major offsetting tax cuts package looms; and if investment picks up in the U.S. behind the tariff wall, things could theoretically turn around fast. Not so much in global exporters to it now stuck with excess production;

The Financial Times calls the tariffs an “astonishing act of self harm” that will “upend the global order and tarnish US prosperity”;

Germany’s outgoing Economy Minister says the move is as bad as Russia’s invasion of Ukraine and the reaction must be commensurate. So, lots of big talk and no action for three years, or the recent shift to massive fiscal stimulus?;

One Bloomberg writer says “Liberation Day isolates America from the rest of the world by incentivizing all other countries to trade with each other instead of America. China now has a golden opportunity to beat America at its own game.” By becoming a mass consumption-based importer?!;

Another compares Trump to China’s Ming dynasty that led to “centuries of decline and humiliation”. As the U.S. aims to build ships again rather than burn the fleet, which is what China did back then and “because markets” did to the U.S. shipbuilding industry;

A more balanced view is this is a radical U.S. gamble that changes how we’ve done things for a generation. Markets obviously won’t like it now, but there are bad potential paths for the U.S. and some good ones. For the world reliant on U.S. end-demand it’s as much of a shock as the recent U.S. pivot on Ukraine and security guarantees was to Europe. Could it trigger equally transformative changes?;

Now the next phase starts as President Trump says: “Every country's called us. That's the beauty of what we do. We put ourselves in the driver's seat. If we would have asked some of these countries, almost, most of these countries, to do us a favor they would have said no. Now, they'll do anything for us.”; but

The EU girds for battle, with French President Macron calling to freeze all investments into the U.S. as a start - just as Europe also negotiates with the U.S. over a security guarantee for Ukraine and buys U.S. LNG;

Meanwhile, the Middle East is heating up, Russia-Ukraine isn’t cooling down, and nobody knows what will happen in an Asia now seeing its economic foundations rocked.

Have a good day and a good weekend.

